WEBVTT

00:02.835 --> 00:05.670
♪ Boy, the way                  
Glenn Miller played ♪           

00:05.672 --> 00:09.340
            ♪ Songs that made   
            The Hit Parade ♪    

00:09.342 --> 00:13.011
♪ Guys like us                  
We had it made ♪                

00:13.013 --> 00:16.280
    ♪ Those were the days ♪     

00:16.282 --> 00:20.284
               <i>♪ And you knew</i>   
           <i>Where you were then ♪</i>

00:20.286 --> 00:23.622
 <i>♪ Girls were girls</i>             
 <i>And men were men ♪</i>             

00:23.624 --> 00:30.394
  <i>♪ Mister, we could use a man</i>  
   <i>Like Herbert Hoover again ♪</i>  

00:30.396 --> 00:32.363
 <i>♪ Didn't need</i>                  
 <i>No welfare state ♪</i>             

00:32.365 --> 00:36.534
             <i>♪ Everybody pulled</i> 
             <i>His weight ♪</i>       

00:36.536 --> 00:40.872
     <i>♪ Gee, our old LaSalle</i>     
           <i>Ran great ♪</i>          

00:40.874 --> 00:46.678
♪ Those were the days ♪         

00:53.653 --> 00:54.753
I ain't wrong.                  

00:54.755 --> 00:56.021
I'm gonna find                  
that <i>Sports Illustrated,</i>        

00:56.023 --> 00:57.288
I'm gonna get that article,     

00:57.290 --> 00:59.691
and I'm gonna show it to you    
in black and white there        

00:59.693 --> 01:00.892
and make you eat your words.    

01:00.894 --> 01:02.060
Get away from me.               

01:02.062 --> 01:04.062
 The magazine is in this house  
        someplace.              

01:04.063 --> 01:06.297
Edith, up there, are you looking
    for that magazine?          

01:06.299 --> 01:08.332
EDITH: Yeah,                    
I'm looking, Archie!            

01:08.334 --> 01:09.868
                I don't hear you
                looking, Edith. 

01:09.870 --> 01:11.169
But I'm looking!                

01:11.171 --> 01:13.805
                I don't hear you
                looking, Edith! 

01:13.807 --> 01:15.239
Daddy, why are you              
wasting your time               

01:15.241 --> 01:16.975
looking for that                
dumb magazine?                  

01:16.977 --> 01:19.610
         Why? To show your dumb 
         husband a thing or two.

01:19.612 --> 01:21.212
             I got a quarter bet
             with him here      

01:21.214 --> 01:24.248
     that Harvey Haddox pitched 
     a perfect no-hit ball game.

01:24.250 --> 01:25.449
Archie, he pitched              
a perfect game                  

01:25.451 --> 01:26.651
for 12 innings.                 

01:26.653 --> 01:28.586
They got a hit off him          
in the 13th,                    

01:28.588 --> 01:29.587
and he lost the game.           

01:29.589 --> 01:30.588
That's not a perfect game.      

01:30.590 --> 01:32.256
            I can still remember
                the headline    

01:32.258 --> 01:33.725
      out of that article there:

01:33.727 --> 01:36.961
"The day that Harvey Haddox was 
  robbed of the no-hit game."   

01:36.963 --> 01:40.865
That's right! He was robbed     
of the no-hit game,             

01:40.867 --> 01:42.500
so he didn't pitch              
the no-hit game.                

01:42.502 --> 01:44.202
            Certainly he did!   

01:44.204 --> 01:45.536
            If you was robbed   
                 of something,  

01:45.538 --> 01:47.338
              you had to have it
              in the first place

01:47.340 --> 01:49.007
    in order to have somebody   
             rob you of it.     

01:50.176 --> 01:52.177
    Look what I found!          

01:52.179 --> 01:54.345
         Good, good. Give me it.
         What the hell is that? 

01:54.347 --> 01:56.247
      My five-year diary.       

01:56.249 --> 01:59.150
              I don't want that!
              Get away from me! 

01:59.152 --> 02:00.518
Ma, you keep a diary?           

02:00.520 --> 02:03.654
            Oh, not anymore,    
          but during the war,   

02:03.656 --> 02:06.825
  every day while your father   
    was in the Army--           

02:06.827 --> 02:08.626
         How many times         
    have I got to tell you?     

02:08.627 --> 02:10.729
     Air Corps, Air Corps,      
        Air Corps!              

02:10.731 --> 02:11.996
    Oh, yeah, that's right.     

02:11.998 --> 02:14.298
            You know            
  what I used to call Archie?   

02:14.300 --> 02:16.400
          My fly-boy.           

02:16.402 --> 02:18.336
[GIGGLING]                      

02:18.338 --> 02:19.337
[LAUGHING]                      

02:19.339 --> 02:22.607
            Aw, clam up, you.   

02:22.609 --> 02:23.975
        I know what you done.   

02:23.977 --> 02:25.243
        You hid that magazine   

02:25.245 --> 02:27.045
        so you wouldn't         
     have to pay me the quarter.

02:27.047 --> 02:28.179
Get outta here.                 

02:28.181 --> 02:29.647
        Listen to this:         

02:29.649 --> 02:33.885
         "May 21, 1943.         

02:33.887 --> 02:38.757
 Dear diary: Had a letter today 
        from Archie B."         

02:38.759 --> 02:42.493
          That's "B",           
     shorthand for Bunker.      

02:44.797 --> 02:48.466
  "Archie said I shouldn't sit  
      under the apple tree      

02:48.468 --> 02:50.969
with anyone else but him.       

02:50.971 --> 02:52.904
     Isn't that romantic?"      

02:52.906 --> 02:55.606
        It is!                  

02:55.608 --> 02:58.676
    "P.S. I don't have          
         an apple tree,         

02:58.678 --> 03:03.014
         so I won't sit         
    under my rubber plant."     

03:03.016 --> 03:08.319
1943, she was still in training 
     for her dingbat wings.     

03:08.321 --> 03:10.421
Come on, Mom,                   
why don't you sit down          

03:10.423 --> 03:11.455
and read us some more?          

03:11.457 --> 03:12.657
All right...                    

03:12.659 --> 03:15.927
         A-ha! I think I know   
         where that magazine is!

03:15.929 --> 03:17.528
        MIKE: Why don't you     
        forget it? You're wrong.

03:17.530 --> 03:19.530
      Get away from me, you.    

03:19.532 --> 03:21.833
    Here's a good one.          

03:21.835 --> 03:24.969
     "September 4th, 1943.      

03:24.971 --> 03:29.140
          "Dear diary:          
 Archie was in town on a pass.  

03:29.142 --> 03:31.609
"He took me to a U.S.O. dance,  

03:31.611 --> 03:34.179
and the funniest thing happened.

03:34.181 --> 03:35.914
     "I'll never forget it.     

03:35.916 --> 03:38.516
"But I'm tired now, dear diary, 

03:38.518 --> 03:41.719
          so I promise          
     to tell you tomorrow."     

03:43.000 --> 03:49.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:53.132 --> 03:55.300
    I wonder what happened.     

03:56.668 --> 03:58.269
             Ma, why don't you  
             read what you wrote

03:58.271 --> 03:59.270
                the next day?   

03:59.272 --> 04:03.007
        Oh, yeah!               

04:03.009 --> 04:04.209
        Here it is:             

04:04.211 --> 04:07.111
      "September 5, 1943.       

04:07.113 --> 04:11.015
          "Dear diary:          
    It rained all day today.    

04:11.017 --> 04:13.417
Nothing much to tell you."      

04:18.490 --> 04:19.690
What happened to                
the funniest thing              

04:19.692 --> 04:20.825
you said you'd                  
never forget?                   

04:22.261 --> 04:25.063
    I guess I forgot.           

04:25.065 --> 04:26.965
      Hey, hey, hey, hey!       

04:26.967 --> 04:29.834
     Look what I found upstairs.

04:29.836 --> 04:31.169
What is it, Archie?             

04:31.171 --> 04:33.037
              Ah, whilst looking
              for my magazine,  

04:33.039 --> 04:34.805
            which I didn't find,

04:34.807 --> 04:37.175
             I ran across a hunk
             of homemade poetry.

04:37.177 --> 04:39.110
         Hey, hey, hey,         
    where did you get that?     

04:39.112 --> 04:41.779
Oh! In that box of junk         
in the bottom of your closet.   

04:41.781 --> 04:43.281
                Give me that.   
                That's mine.    

04:43.283 --> 04:45.884
What do you mean? Don't you want
  to share it with the world?   

04:45.886 --> 04:47.685
             You got no right   
             going into my room.

04:47.687 --> 04:50.188
Hold it, hotshot.               

04:50.190 --> 04:52.757
You're only borrowing           
that room from me               

04:52.759 --> 04:56.861
because Gloria happens          
to be your roommate.            

04:56.863 --> 04:58.462
But the room                    
is still in my house,           

04:58.464 --> 05:00.798
which means I got a right       
to search it.                   

05:00.800 --> 05:03.234
        We're living in the     
        Watergate Hotel here.   

05:07.172 --> 05:09.540
    You got no right snooping   
          around in my things!  

05:09.542 --> 05:12.243
I was only looking              
for one of my things,           

05:12.245 --> 05:15.280
and I found this thing.         

05:15.282 --> 05:17.681
And wait till you get           
an earful of it there, Edith.   

05:17.683 --> 05:19.951
"No girl's as sweet             
As my true love                 

05:19.953 --> 05:21.319
You were sent                   
From heaven above"              

05:21.321 --> 05:22.586
             All right, give it.
             Come on.           

05:22.588 --> 05:24.923
"You fill my days...            
             All right, come on.

05:24.925 --> 05:28.393
"With sheer                     
delight...  Hand it over,       
                   will you?    

05:28.395 --> 05:30.295
"Throughout the day,            
Throughout the night...         

05:30.297 --> 05:31.695
All right, come on.             
Hand it over.                   

05:31.697 --> 05:35.266
          Ah, we got a regular  
        Edgar Allan Polack here.

05:35.268 --> 05:36.267
Come on, now!                   

05:36.269 --> 05:37.468
I'm not kidding around!         

05:37.470 --> 05:39.003
              Give me that. That
              poem is personal. 

05:39.005 --> 05:40.271
        Personal?               
    I'll say it's personal.     

05:40.273 --> 05:42.273
Hey, Edith, wait till you       
     hear the rest of this.     

05:42.275 --> 05:43.641
                Oh, Archie...   

05:43.643 --> 05:45.743
         "A touch of your lips, 
        And my heart's on fire. 

05:45.745 --> 05:46.978
        A glimpse of your--"    

05:46.980 --> 05:49.247
        I'm going to say        
     the word "chests" here     

05:49.249 --> 05:52.917
because we're in mixed company--

05:52.919 --> 05:56.287
  "A glimpse of your chests,    
And I'm mad with desire"        

05:56.289 --> 05:58.889
  Oh, my, I'm all goose bumps.  

05:58.891 --> 06:00.191
          Ah, shut up.          

06:01.726 --> 06:02.760
Look, Archie,                   
I'm telling you,                

06:02.762 --> 06:04.728
I put up with a lot             
around here,                    

06:04.730 --> 06:06.931
but there is one thing          
I will not put up with,         

06:06.933 --> 06:08.333
and that is having              
my privacy invaded.             

06:08.335 --> 06:09.467
            Whoop-de-do.        

06:09.469 --> 06:11.336
          Well, then, what about
          my privacy, Daddy?    

06:11.338 --> 06:12.937
                Michael wrote   
                that poem to me.

06:12.939 --> 06:14.172
              To you, huh?      

06:14.174 --> 06:16.707
      Then why does it say      
     up on top, "To Vicky"?     

06:16.709 --> 06:18.176
            Let me see that.    

06:18.178 --> 06:20.211
                    ARCHIE: Hey!

06:20.213 --> 06:22.746
It looks to me like the Meathead
was glimpsing a few chests      

06:22.748 --> 06:24.748
  before he run across yours.   

06:30.055 --> 06:31.255
                Who's Vicky?    

06:32.858 --> 06:36.194
Ah, it's nobody, just a girl    
I used to know a long time ago. 

06:36.196 --> 06:37.595
             Michael, you said  
             you wrote this poem

06:37.597 --> 06:39.163
            especially to me,   

06:39.165 --> 06:42.233
    and it wasn't "To Vicky"    
    then, it was "To Gloria."   

06:42.235 --> 06:45.136
Well, yeah, but...              
it was my best poem!            

06:45.138 --> 06:46.337
I wanted you to have it!        

06:46.339 --> 06:47.972
                 Michael,       
              you lied to me.   

06:47.974 --> 06:50.141
        You never even really   
              wrote me a poem.  

06:50.143 --> 06:52.843
Gloria, I did better than that. 
I married you!                  

06:52.845 --> 06:54.245
      That wasn't better.       

06:54.247 --> 06:56.680
        You should have         
      kept writing poems.       

06:56.682 --> 06:58.483
    Hey, I don't have           
     to take that from you!     

06:58.485 --> 07:00.118
What else have you              
lied to me about?               

07:00.120 --> 07:01.886
            Nothing!            
That's a lie!                   

07:01.888 --> 07:03.521
Gloria. please,                 
what do you want from me?       

07:03.523 --> 07:04.522
                 [SOBS] Michael!

07:04.524 --> 07:07.825
        You gave me a used poem!

07:07.827 --> 07:10.594
Gloria, your father acts        
like a storm trooper,           

07:10.596 --> 07:12.263
he turns our bedroom            
into a police state,            

07:12.265 --> 07:14.298
and all you care about is       
a lousy poem?!                  

07:14.300 --> 07:16.100
         Because you lied to me!

07:16.102 --> 07:18.169
                 How can I ever 
            trust you again?!   

07:18.171 --> 07:19.603
What about trusting your father?

07:19.605 --> 07:21.005
            How are you gonna   
                trust him again?

07:21.007 --> 07:23.207
    The next thing you know,    
 he's gonna be bugging our bed! 

07:23.209 --> 07:25.976
    The only bug in your bed    
    is when you hop into it.    

07:27.279 --> 07:29.013
Oh, that's it! That's it.       

07:29.015 --> 07:31.282
I don't have to take that       
        from you.               

07:31.284 --> 07:34.185
    What do I need this for?    
        I must be crazy!        

07:34.187 --> 07:36.387
      I'm not gonna stay in     
      this house another minute.

07:36.389 --> 07:38.256
  Between you and your father,  
    you're driving me crazy!    

07:38.258 --> 07:40.491
Out there, I will be able       
    to get a little freedom.    

07:40.493 --> 07:42.293
     I will be able to get      
    a little privacy.           

07:42.295 --> 07:45.296
    You'll be able to apply     
for a little welfare too.       

07:45.298 --> 07:47.031
            Goodbye, goodbye.   

07:47.033 --> 07:48.466
            You can send my     
            clothes to Lionel's.

07:48.468 --> 07:50.000
Archie, he's leaving!           
Say something.                  

07:50.002 --> 07:50.868
                     Bye!       

07:52.471 --> 07:54.472
          [YELLING INCOHERENTLY]

07:57.476 --> 07:59.043
        [BAWLING] Ma...         

08:02.448 --> 08:05.283
Oh, oh...                       

08:05.285 --> 08:06.717
     [CHUCKLES]                 

08:06.719 --> 08:09.587
  EDITH: He'll be back as soon  
as he gets over being mad.      

08:09.589 --> 08:12.123
     Yeah, which should be      
    around dinnertime.          

08:12.125 --> 08:13.991
                Shut up!        
        What?                   

08:13.993 --> 08:15.659
                        Shut up!

08:15.661 --> 08:17.695
  If you hadn't been snooping   
    where you didn't belong,    

08:17.697 --> 08:20.531
I wouldn't have found out       
  what I didn't want to know!   

08:20.533 --> 08:22.533
You've been trying to get       
Michael out of this house       

08:22.535 --> 08:23.801
         for two years!         

08:23.803 --> 08:25.035
    Well, you got your wish,    

08:25.037 --> 08:26.471
    and I hope you're happy,    
          you monster!          

08:26.473 --> 08:27.572
    What?                       

08:27.574 --> 08:29.207
              Did you hear what 
              your daughter said

08:29.209 --> 08:30.508
                  to her father?

08:30.510 --> 08:34.044
Yeah. I couldn't help it.       
I was standing right here.      

08:35.947 --> 08:37.414
              What's she yelling
              at me for?        

08:37.417 --> 08:38.881
            That ain't my fault!

08:38.884 --> 08:40.818
    Hey, little girl,           
    it ain't my fault           

08:40.820 --> 08:42.820
    that the Meathead           
only had one poem in him,       

08:42.822 --> 08:46.991
  and then he spread it around  
    like fertilizer...          

08:46.993 --> 08:48.726
which, by the way, it is.       

08:48.728 --> 08:51.996
             Oh, Archie, I think
             you were wrong     

08:51.998 --> 08:53.897
          to go into their room.

08:53.899 --> 08:56.967
          After all, they got   
    a right to their privacy.   

08:56.969 --> 08:58.869
Well, I happen to agree         
with my government.             

08:58.871 --> 09:00.671
If you ain't got nothing        
to be ashamed of,               

09:00.673 --> 09:02.206
you don't need no privacy.      

09:02.208 --> 09:06.344
        Mike's poem is personal,
             like my diary.     

09:06.346 --> 09:09.547
Oh! But if I want to read       
your diary, I can read it.      

09:09.549 --> 09:11.382
          [GASPS] No, you can't!

09:12.518 --> 09:15.719
            My diary is private.

09:15.721 --> 09:18.922
    Are you telling me that     
you would keep secrets from me? 

09:18.924 --> 09:20.724
    Some secrets, yes.          

09:20.726 --> 09:23.127
  No secrets, no!               

09:23.129 --> 09:24.395
We'll have this out             
right now.                      

09:24.397 --> 09:25.996
I'm your husband,               
and I say to you,               

09:25.998 --> 09:27.365
"Give me that diary."           

09:27.367 --> 09:30.401
      [GASPS] And I'm your wife,
        and I say, "no."        

09:32.371 --> 09:34.172
 GLORIA: I'm going to Trudy's.  

09:34.174 --> 09:36.607
Hold it, there, hold it.        
You ain't going no place.       

09:36.609 --> 09:39.743
         Take your hands off me.

09:39.745 --> 09:40.844
Take your hands off her!        

09:40.846 --> 09:41.845
      I didn't touch her!       

09:41.847 --> 09:43.013
          Gloria...             

09:43.015 --> 09:44.649
                I'm sorry, Ma,  
             but there's nothing

09:44.651 --> 09:46.184
                to stay here for
                anymore!        

09:46.186 --> 09:49.554
            [GASPS] Archie!     
    Ain't you gonna stop her?   

09:49.556 --> 09:50.588
No, I ain't!                    

09:50.590 --> 09:51.455
                 Oh!            

09:52.824 --> 09:54.225
             Now, wait a minute,
                wait a minute.  

09:54.227 --> 09:55.560
Where are you going?            

09:55.562 --> 09:58.329
             I'm her mother.    
         That's where I'm going.

09:59.498 --> 10:03.133
Edith, you get                  
back inside this door...        

10:03.135 --> 10:04.335
That's more like it.            

10:04.337 --> 10:05.803
                 And sit down   
             in your chair here.

10:05.805 --> 10:07.805
  We're going to have a little  
talk about your daughter,       

10:07.807 --> 10:09.407
    mouthing off to me          
      the way she done...       

10:09.409 --> 10:10.608
  Who does she think she is--   

10:10.610 --> 10:11.475
                    [DOOR SLAMS]

10:21.786 --> 10:24.555
    I'm in a nuthouse.          

10:32.764 --> 10:35.433
    No, operator, operator,     
    just listen to me, huh?     

10:35.435 --> 10:39.003
     The name of the party      
    is Whiteman or Lightman     

10:39.005 --> 10:40.138
    or something like that.     

10:40.140 --> 10:42.306
 The first name is Trudy, see?  

10:42.308 --> 10:43.707
        She lives               
at one of them apartments       

10:43.709 --> 10:46.010
        over there              
     on Northern Boulevard.     

10:46.012 --> 10:47.278
    Uh, listen to me.           

10:47.280 --> 10:50.748
 I just want the address there. 

10:50.750 --> 10:52.116
     I can't give you that.     

10:52.118 --> 10:55.819
        I'm trying              
to find that out from you.      

10:55.821 --> 10:56.887
      Whiteman, Lightman.       

10:56.889 --> 10:59.157
        Can't you look--        

10:59.159 --> 11:00.991
        Listen, can--           

11:00.993 --> 11:03.327
          Listen, can--         

11:03.329 --> 11:04.629
        [STAMMERS]              

11:05.830 --> 11:07.298
        Forget it!              

11:20.412 --> 11:23.481
  Uh, hello there, Jefferson.   
  This is Archie Bunker here.   

11:23.483 --> 11:25.183
         Uh, put Lionel         
    on the phone, huh?          

11:27.386 --> 11:29.387
     I know it's 1:00 a.m.,     

11:29.389 --> 11:32.156
  But youse people don't sleep  
      on a Saturday night.      

11:34.826 --> 11:36.427
Hold it, hold it, hold it,      
            hold it!            

11:36.429 --> 11:38.629
  There's no call to be using   
  that kind of language here.   

11:38.631 --> 11:40.264
  I didn't say nothing like...  

11:40.266 --> 11:41.799
        L-Listen to me.         

11:41.801 --> 11:43.801
  I'm just trying to find out   
    where my son-in-law is.     

11:43.803 --> 11:45.703
    I think he's over there.    

11:45.705 --> 11:46.904
     Aw, what do you mean,      

11:46.906 --> 11:50.241
      you don't let whitey      
        on the premises?        

11:50.243 --> 11:52.510
  I know he's over there. J--   

11:52.512 --> 11:55.045
         Hello? Hello?          

11:55.047 --> 11:56.380
        You crumb.              

11:57.583 --> 11:58.782
                [DOORBELL RINGS]

11:58.784 --> 12:00.618
        Oh, well.               

12:00.620 --> 12:01.752
        And about time.         

12:01.754 --> 12:03.954
    I ought to let you          
     stay out there, Edith.     

12:03.956 --> 12:04.955
      Oh, hi, Mr. Bunker.       

12:04.957 --> 12:06.924
Oh, hiya, Lionel.               
Where's Mike?                   

12:06.926 --> 12:08.326
            He went straight    
            home to my house.   

12:08.328 --> 12:09.594
We just came from a movie.      

12:09.596 --> 12:11.395
        Well, then your old man 
